## How we work

### Monthly engineer registration

Once the volunteers have been given approvals in the [relevant issue](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/fulfillment-meta/-/issues/206), they should book the times or days they'll be working on the initiative for the current/next month, ideally beforehand.

1. Book the day using your name as a new event in the [Fulfillment InfraDev calendar](https://calendar.google.com/calendar/u/2?cid=Y19yYjIzYXRtbzhkaTMwMTdsdGtob2M2ZWdkMEBncm91cC5jYWxlbmRhci5nb29nbGUuY29t)
1. Ping your manager to check the time you are going to spend on the initiative and dates are OK
1. Keep the calendar updated

### Picking and working on issues

Given the small percentage of time dedicated by each engineer, the workflow is a bit different to that of GitLab in order to be more efficient. Therefore, engineers can pick any unassigned issue that is not blocked.

1. Use the [Fulfillment InfraDev Kanban board](https://gitlab.com/groups/gitlab-com/-/boards/2710654?&label_name[]=Fulfillment%3A%3AInfraDev)
1. Pick an issue from the top that is unassigned and either `ready for development` or `in dev` or `in review`
1. At the end of your shift/day please either close the issue if done, or leave an update for the next engineer and unassign yourself from the issue. If you are working on it on consecutive days, you can keep yourself assigned. The following template can be used:

```
## Async issue update
1. Please provide a summary of the current status and blockers
1. What would be the focus for the next engineer that picks this issue?

/unassign @yourhandlehere
```

